ggplot2

Pawan

ggplot2 is an open-source of data visualization and graphical representation package for the R programming language. This package is created by Hadley Wickham.

Installation

We can install ggplot2 just using this command

install.packages("ggplot2")

Note: ggplot2 is also included in the tidyverse package.

Loading the ggplot2 package

library(ggplot2)

Lets start plotting with ggplot2

There are three basic part of ggplot
i) First we to define our data from which we want to plot our graph

  1. mapping, here we can define our aesthetics like x-axis, y-axis, color, linetpye, shape, etc. aes(x, y, color)

  2. geom function, geom function define our type of graph that we want to plot, like scatter plot, line plot, bar plot, box plot, etc. geom_line(), geom_point()

ggplot(data, aes(x, y)) + geom_function()

Lets start to plot a simple graph

library(ggplot2)
mtcars->df

# Line chart
ggplot(df, aes(x = mpg, y = disp)) +
  geom_line() ->p1
p1

# Scatter plot
ggplot(df, aes(x = hp, y = wt)) +
  geom_point() ->p2
p2

ggplot2 provide many geom function as shown below:

geom_point() Scatter Plot

geom_line() Line plot

geom_bar() Bar charts

geom_blank() Draw a blank plot

geom_boxplot() Box plot

geom_density() Density plot

geom_dotplot() Dot plot

geom_histogram() Histograms

geom_map() Map plot

geom_polygon() Polygons plot

geom_ribbon() or geom_area() Ribbons and area plots

geom_segment() or geom_curve() Line segments and curves

geom_smooth() or stat_smooth() Conditional means

geom_label() or geom_text() Text plot

geom_violin() Violin plot

Facet

library(ggplot2)
iris->dataset

ggplot(dataset, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point() ->p

p+ facet_wrap(~Species)->p
p

Theme

The ggplot2 package have different themes. By default it uses the theme_grey (theme_gray()), so we dont need to specify it. Themes provided by ggplot are below

theme_gray() default ggplot2 theme with a grey background and white gridlines
theme_bw() dark and light (black and white) ggplot2 theme
theme_linedraw() uses black lines on white backgrounds only
theme_light() similar to linedraw() but with grey lines
theme_dark() lines on a dark background
theme_minimal() no background annotations
theme_classic() theme with no grid lines
theme_void() empty theme with no elements

We can also modify the plot base size by using base_size argument in the theme functions.

library(ggplot2)

iris->dataset

# Scatter Plot
ggplot(dataset, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point() ->p

p+ facet_wrap(~Species)->p

## theme_bw()
p+theme_bw(base_size=20)->p1
p1

## theme_dark()
p+theme_dark()->p2
p2

Lab funtion

Whit using of labs() function we can set a title, subtitle, caption, and axis title of the plot.

library(ggplot2)

iris->dataset

# Scatter Plot
ggplot(dataset, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point() ->p

p+ facet_wrap(~Species)->p

## theme_bw()
p+theme_bw(base_size=20)->p

## Lab Function
p+labs(title = "Title of the plot",
       subtitle = "Subtitle of the plot",
       caption = "Caption of the plot",
       x = "x-axis",
       y = "y-axis")->p
p

Modify plot with theme function

We can modify our plot with the use of `theme() function. Here we can define position of the title, subtile, caption, panel background, legend position, and many more things. You can define your own theme, size, color, shape of the plot as you want. Below given some use theme arguments which are also my favart.

theme(
  axis.title,        ## for both axis
  axis.title.x,      ## for x axis
  axis.title.y,      ## for y axis
  axis.text,         ## for both axis
  axis.text.x,       ## for x axis
  axis.text.y,       ## for y axis
  axis.ticks,        ## for both axis
  axis.ticks.x,      ## for x axis
  axis.ticks.y,      ## for y axis
  axis.line,         ## for both axis
  axis.line.x,       ## for x axis
  axis.line.y,       ## for y axis
  legend.background,
  legend.margin,
  legend.text,
  legend.title,
  legend.position,
  legend.direction,
  legend.box,
  panel.background,
  panel.border,
  panel.grid,
  panel.grid.major,
  panel.grid.minor,
  plot.background,
  plot.title,
  plot.subtitle,
  plot.caption,
  plot.tag,
  plot.margin,
  strip.background,
  strip.background.x,
  strip.background.y,
  strip.text,
  strip.text.x,
  strip.text.y)

With the using of these arguments we are able to modify plot, these arguments
element_line() use for line
element_rect() use for color
element_text() use for text
element_blank() use for blank

For example

theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 1),
      plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 0.5),
      panel.background = element_rect(fill = "yellow"),
      axis.text = element_text(size = 2))
library(ggplot2)

iris->dataset

# Scatter Plot
ggplot(dataset, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color = Species)) +
  geom_point() ->p

p+ facet_wrap(~Species)->p

## theme of the plot
p+theme_bw()->p

## Lab Function
p+labs(title = "Title of the plot",
       subtitle = "Subtitle of the plot",
       caption = "Caption of the plot")->p

## theme function
p+theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        plot.title = element_text(family = "serif",              # Font family
                                  face = "bold",                 # Font face
                                  size = 15,                     # Font size
                                  hjust = 1,                     # Horizontal adjustment
                                  vjust = 1),                   # Vertical adjustment
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 1),
        plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0.1),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "yellow"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 2),
        strip.background = element_rect(fill = "pink"),
        strip.text = element_text(size = 9),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "green"),
        panel.border = element_rect(linetype = "dashed"),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "black"))->p 
p

Combine multiple plot

The ggplot2 package doesnt providing function to arrange multiples plots in a single figure, but there are some packages, that allow combine multiples plots into a single figure with custom layouts, width, height, such as cowplot, gridExtra, patchwork. (https://medium.com/@pawanjangra1198/combining-plots-in-ggplot2-9699acaa2942#6632-36f5b0859cff)

library(ggplot2)

mtcars->df

# Box plot
p1 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = "", y = mpg)) +
  geom_boxplot()

# Density plot
p2 <- ggplot() +
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, geom = "density",
                xlim = c(-3, 3), fill = "white") 

# Line chart
p3 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = mpg, y = disp)) +
  geom_line(color = "gray20")

# Scatter plot
p4 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = hp, y = wt)) +
  geom_point(color = "gray20")

# View the plots
p1

p2

p3

p4

The gridExtra package provides the grid.arrange function to combine several plots on a single figure.

# install.packages("gridExtra")
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

# Combine the plots with gridExtra
grid.arrange(p2, p3, p1, p4)
